
<section xml:id="sec_limit_analytically">
  <title>Finding Limits Analytically</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>In <xref ref="sec_limit_intro">Section</xref> we explored the concept of the limit without a strict definition, meaning we could only make approximations. In the previous section we gave the definition of the limit and demonstrated how to use it to verify our approximations were correct. Thus far, our method of finding a limit is 1) make a really good approximation either graphically or numerically, and 2) verify our approximation is correct using a <m>\varepsilon</m>-<m>\delta</m> proof.</p>

    <p>Recognizing that <m>\varepsilon</m>-<m>\delta</m> proofs are cumbersome, this section gives a series of theorems which allow us to find limits much more quickly and intuitively.</p>

    <p>Suppose that <m>\lim_{x\to 2} f(x)=2</m> and <m>\lim_{x\to 2} g(x) = 3</m>. What is <m>\lim_{x\to 2}(f(x)+g(x))</m>? Intuition tells us that the limit should be 5, as we expect limits to behave in a nice way. The following theorem states that already established limits do behave nicely.</p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm_limit_algebra">
      <title>Basic Limit Properties</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, <m>L</m> and <m>K</m> be real numbers, let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, and let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be functions with the following limits: <index><main>limit</main><sub>properties</sub></index>
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to c}f(x) = L \textit{ and } \lim_{x\to c} g(x) = K.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>The following limits hold.</p>

        <dl>
          <li><title>Constants:</title><p> <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to c} b = b</m></p></li>

          <li><title>Identity</title><p><m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to c} x = c</m></p></li>

          <li><title>Sums/Differences:</title><p> <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to c}(f(x)\pm g(x)) = L\pm K</m></p></li>

          <li><title>Scalar Multiples:</title><p>	<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to c} b\cdot f(x) = bL</m></p></li>

          <li><title>Products:</title><p>	<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to c} f(x)\cdot g(x) = LK</m></p></li>

          <li><title>Quotients:</title><p> <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to c} f(x)/g(x) = L/K</m>, (<m>K\neq 0)</m></p></li>

          <li><title>Powers:</title><p> 	<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to c} f(x)^n = L^n</m></p></li>

          <li><title>Roots:</title><p>	<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to c} \sqrt[n]{f(x)} = \sqrt[n]{L}</m></p></li>
          <li>(If <m>n</m> is even, <m>L</m> must be non-negative.)</li>

          <li><title>Compositions:</title><p> Adjust our previously given limit situation to:
              <me>
                \lim_{x\to c}f(x) = L,\ \lim_{x\to L} g(x) = M \textit{ and } g(L)=M .
              </me>
              Then <m>\ds \lim_{x\to c}g(f(x)) = M</m>.</p></li>
              <li>In other words, <m>\ds \lim_{x\to c}g(f(x)) = g \left(\lim_{x\to c} f(x) \right)=g(L)</m>, provided that <m>g(L)</m> is defined.</li>
        </dl>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <!--
    <p>We make a note about Property <hash />8: when <m>n</m> is even, <m>L</m> must be greater than 0. If <m>n</m> is odd, then the statement is true for all <m>L</m>.</p>-->

    <p>We apply the theorem to an example.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex_basic_limit_1">
      <title>Using basic limit properties</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Let
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to 2} f(x)=2,\lim_{x\to 2} g(x) = 3 \textit{ and  } p(x) = 3x^2-5x+7.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>Find the following limits:</p>

        <ol cols="2" >
          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to 2} \big(f(x) + g(x)\big)</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to 2} \big(5f(x) + g(x)^2\big)</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to 2} p(x)</m></p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ol>
          <li><p>Using the Sum/Difference rule, we know that <m>\ds \lim_{x\to 2} \big(f(x) + g(x)\big) = 2+3 =5</m>.</p></li>

          <li><p>Using the Scalar Multiple, Sum/Difference and Power rules, we find that <m>\ds \lim_{x\to 2} \big(5f(x) + g(x)^2\big) = 5\cdot 2 + 3^2 = 19.</m></p></li>

          <li><p>Here we combine the Power, Scalar Multiple, Sum/Difference and Constant Rules. We show quite a few steps, but in general these can be omitted:
              <md>
                <mrow>\lim_{x\to 2} p(x) \amp = \lim_{x\to 2} (3x^2-5x+7)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \lim_{x\to 2} 3x^2-\lim_{x\to 2} 5x+\lim_{x\to 2}7</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = 3\cdot 2^2 - 5\cdot 2+7</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = 9</mrow>
              </md>
            </p></li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>Part 3 of the previous example demonstrates how the limit of a quadratic polynomial can be determined using the properties of <xref ref="thm_limit_algebra">Theorem</xref>. Not only that, recognize that
      <me>
        \lim_{x\to 2} p(x) = 9 = p(2);
      </me>
      i.e., the limit at 2 was found just by plugging 2 into the function. This holds true for all polynomials, and also for rational functions (which are quotients of polynomials), as stated in the following theorem.</p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm_poly_rat">
      <title>Limits of Polynomial and Rational Functions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> be polynomials and <m>c</m> a real number. Then:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} p(x) = p(c)</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \frac{p(x)}{q(x)} = \frac{p(c)}{q(c)}</m>, where <m>q(c) \neq 0</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="ex_limit_rat">
      <title>Finding a limit of a rational function</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Using <xref ref="thm_poly_rat">Theorem</xref>, find
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to -1} \frac{3x^2-5x+1}{x^4-x^2+3}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Using <xref ref="thm_poly_rat">Theorem</xref>, we can quickly state that
          <md>
            <mrow>\lim_{x\to -1}\frac{3x^2-5x+1}{x^4-x^2+3} \amp = \frac{3(-1)^2-5(-1)+1}{(-1)^4-(-1)^2+3}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{9}{3} </mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =3.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>It was likely frustrating in <xref ref="sec_limit_def">Section</xref> to do a lot of work to prove that
      <me>
        \lim_{x\to 2} x^2 = 4
      </me>
      as it seemed fairly obvious. The previous theorems state that many functions behave in such an <q>obvious</q> fashion, as demonstrated by the rational function in <xref ref="ex_limit_rat">Example</xref>.</p>

    <p>Polynomial and rational functions are not the only functions to behave in such a predictable way. The following theorem gives a list of functions whose behavior is particularly <q>nice</q> in terms of limits. In the next section, we will give a formal name to these functions that behave <q>nicely.</q></p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm_lim_continuous">
      <title>Special Limits</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>c</m> be a real number in the domain of the given function and let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. The following limits hold:</p>

        <ol cols="3" >
          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \fi{\sin}{x} = \fi{\sin}{c}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \fi{\cos}{x} = \cos c</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \fi{\tan}{x}= \fi{\tan}{c}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \fi{\csc}{x} = \fi{\csc}{c}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \fi{\sec}{x} = \fi{\sec}{c}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \fi{\cot}{x} = \fi{\cot}{c}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} a^x = a^c</m> (<m>a>0</m>)</p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \fi{\ln}{x} = \fi{\ln}{c}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to c} \sqrt[n]{x} = \sqrt[n]{c}</m></p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="ex_limit_1">
      <title>Evaluating limits analytically</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Evaluate the following limits.</p>

        <ol cols="2" >
          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to \pi} \fi{\cos}{x}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to 3} (\fi{\sec^2}{x} - \fi{\tan^2}{x})</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to \pi/2} \fi{\cos}{x}\fi{\sin}{x}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to 1} e^{\fi{\ln}{x}}</m></p></li>

          <li><p><m>\ds \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\fi{\sin}{x}}{x}</m></p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ol>
          <li><p>This is a straightforward application of <xref ref="thm_lim_continuous">Theorem</xref>. <m>\ds \lim_{x\to \pi} \fi{\cos}{x} = \cos \pi = -1</m>.</p></li>

          <li><p>We can approach this in at least two ways. First, by directly applying <xref ref="thm_lim_continuous">Theorem</xref>, we have:
              <me>
                \lim_{x\to 3} (\fi{\sec^2}{x} - \fi{\tan^2}{x}) = \fi{\sec^2}{3}-\fi{\tan^2}{3}.
              </me>
              Using the Pythagorean Theorem, this last expression is 1; therefore
              <me>
                \lim_{x\to 3} (\fi{\sec^2}{x} - \fi{\tan^2}{x}) = 1.
              </me>
              We can also use the Pythagorean Theorem from the start.
              <me>
                \lim_{x\to 3} (\fi{\sec^2}{x} - \fi{\tan^2}{x}) = \lim_{x\to 3} 1 = 1,
              </me>
              using the Constant limit rule. Either way, we find the limit is 1.</p></li>

          <li><p>Applying the Product limit rule of <xref ref="thm_limit_algebra">Theorem</xref> and <xref ref="thm_lim_continuous">Theorem</xref> gives
              <me>
                \ds \lim_{x\to \pi/2} \fi{\cos}{x}\fi{\sin}{x} = \cos (\pi/2)\sin(\pi/2) = 0\cdot 1 = 0.
              </me>
            </p></li>

          <li><p>Again, we can approach this in two ways. First, we can use the exponential/logarithmic identity that <m>e^{\fi{\ln}{x}} = x</m> and evaluate <m>\ds \lim_{x\to 1} e^{\fi{\ln}{x}} = \lim_{x\to 1} x = 1.</m> 

              We can also use the limit Composition Rule of <xref ref="thm_limit_algebra">Theorem</xref>. Using <xref ref="thm_lim_continuous">Theorem</xref>, we have <m>\ds \lim_{x\to 1}\fi{\ln}{x} = \ln 1 = 0</m> and <m>\ds\lim_{x\to 0} e^x= e^0=1</m>, satisfying the conditions of the Composition Rule. Applying this rule,
              <me>
                \ds \lim_{x\to 1} e^{\fi{\ln}{x}} = e^{\lim_{x\to 1} \fi{\ln}{x}}=e^{\fi{\ln}{1}}  = e^0 = 1.
              </me>
              Both approaches are valid, giving the same result.</p></li>

          <li><p>We encountered this limit in <xref ref="sec_limit_intro">Section</xref>. Applying our theorems, we attempt to find the limit as
              <me>
                 \lim_{x\to 0}\frac{\fi{\sin}{x}}{x}\rightarrow \frac{\sin 0}{0} \text{ Which is of the form } \frac{0}{0}
              </me>
              This, of course, violates a condition of <xref ref="thm_limit_algebra">Theorem</xref>, as the limit of the denominator is not allowed to be 0. Therefore, we are still unable to evaluate this limit with tools we currently have at hand.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>The section could have been titled <q>Using Known Limits to Find Unknown Limits.</q> By knowing certain limits of functions, we can find limits involving sums, products, powers, etc., of these functions. We further the development of such comparative tools with the Squeeze Theorem, a clever and intuitive way to find the value of some limits.</p>

    <p>Before stating this theorem formally, suppose we have functions <m>f</m>, <m>g</m> and <m>h</m> where <m>g</m> always takes on values between <m>f</m> and <m>h</m>; that is, for all <m>x</m> in an interval,
      <me>
        f(x) \leq g(x) \leq h(x).
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>If <m>f</m> and <m>h</m> have the same limit at <m>c</m>, and <m>g</m> is always <q>squeezed</q> between them, then <m>g</m> must have the same limit as well. That is what the Squeeze Theorem states.</p>
    <todo>Alex, add a squeeze theorem graph</todo>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_sqz">
      <title>Squeeze Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>f</m>, <m>g</m> and <m>h</m> be functions on an open interval <m>I</m> containing <m>c</m> such that for all <m>x</m> in <m>I</m>,
          <me>
            f(x)\leq g(x) \leq h(x).
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>If
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to c} f(x) = L = \lim_{x\to c} h(x),
          </me>
          then
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to c} g(x) = L.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p><index><main>limit</main><sub>Squeeze Theorem</sub></index><index><main>Squeeze Theorem</main></index></p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>It can take some work to figure out appropriate functions by which to <q>squeeze</q> the given function of which you are trying to evaluate a limit. However, that is generally the only place work is necessary; the theorem makes the <q>evaluating the limit part</q> very simple.</p>

    <p>We use the Squeeze Theorem in the following example to finally prove that <m>\ds \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\fi{\sin}{x}}{x} = 1</m>.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex_limit_sinx_prove">
      <title>Using the Squeeze Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Use the Squeeze Theorem to show that
          <me>
            \ds \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\fi{\sin}{x}}{x} = 1.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>We begin by considering the unit circle. Each point on the unit circle has coordinates <m>(\cos \theta,\sin \theta)</m> for some angle <m>\theta</m> as shown in <xref ref="fig_squeeze_sinx">Figure</xref>. Using similar triangles, we can extend the line from the origin through the point to the point <m>(1,\tan \theta)</m>, as shown. (Here we are assuming that <m>0\leq \theta \leq \pi/2</m>. Later we will show that we can also consider <m>\theta \leq 0</m>.)</p>

        <figure xml:id="fig_squeeze_sinx" >
          <caption>The unit circle and related triangles.</caption>
          <!-- START figures/fig_squeeze1.tex -->
          <image xml:id="img_squeeze_sinx" >
            <description></description>
            <latex-image-code>
              <![CDATA[
              \begin{tikzpicture}[x=.4\marginparwidth,y=.4\marginparwidth,>=stealth]
              %\begin{axis}[ymin=-1.1,ymax=1.1,xmin=-1.1,xmax=1.1,xtick={1},ytick={1},]
              %\end{axis}
              \draw [thick] (0,0) node [shift={(10pt,4pt)}] {\scriptsize$\theta$} circle (1);
              \draw [<->,thick] (-1.1,0) -- (1.1,0);
              \draw [<->,thick] (0,-1.1) -- (0,1.1);
              \draw [thick] (0,0) -- (1,.839) node [above] {\scriptsize$(1,\tan \theta)$}-- (1,0) -- (.766,.643);
              \fill [black] (1,.839) circle (1.5pt);
              \fill [black] (.766,.643) node [left] {\scriptsize$(\cos \theta,\sin \theta)$} circle (1.5pt);
              \fill [black] (1,0) node [below right] {\scriptsize$(1,0)$} circle (1.5pt);
              \end{tikzpicture}
              % this is the sqrt[x] on [0,5]
              ]]>
            </latex-image-code>
          </image>
          <!-- figures/fig_squeeze1.tex END -->
        </figure>

        <p><xref ref="fig_squeeze_sinx">Figure</xref> shows three regions have been constructed in the first quadrant, two triangles and a sector of a circle, which are also drawn below. The area of the large triangle is <m>\frac12\tan\theta</m>; the area of the sector is <m>\theta/2</m>; the area of the triangle contained inside the sector is <m>\frac12\sin\theta</m>. It is then clear from the diagram that</p>

        <figure>
