      <exercise>
        <webwork seed="1">
          <setup>
            <var name="">
              <static></static>
            </var>
            <pg-code>
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p>Let <m>f(x) = 0</m> and <m>\ds g(x) = \frac xx</m>.</p>

            <ol>
              <li><p>Show why <m>\ds \lim_{x\to2} f(x)=0</m>.</p></li>

              <li><p>Show why <m>\ds \lim_{x\to0} g(x) = 1</m>.</p></li>

              <li><p>Show why <m>\ds \lim_{x\to2} g\big(f(x)\big)</m> does not exist.</p></li>

              <li><p>Show why the answer to part (c) does not violate the Composition Rule of <xref ref="thm_limit_algebra">Theorem</xref>.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <ol>
              <li><p>Apply Part 1 of <xref ref="thm_limit_algebra">Theorem</xref>.</p></li>

              <li><p>Apply <xref ref="thm_limit_allbut1">Theorem</xref>; <m>g(x) = \frac xx</m> is the same as <m>g(x) = 1</m> everywhere except at <m>x=0</m>. Thus <m>\ds\lim_{x\to0} g(x) = \lim_{x\to 0} 1 = 1.</m></p></li>

              <li><p>The function <m>f(x)</m> is always 0, so <m>g\big(f(x)\big)</m> is never defined as <m>g(x)</m> is not defined at <m>x=0</m>. Therefore the limit does not exist.</p></li>

              <li><p>The Composition Rule requires that <m>\ds\lim_{x\to0} g(x)</m> be equal to <m>g(0)</m>. They are not equal, so the conditions of the Composition Rule are not satisfied, and hence the rule is not violated.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </answer>
          <solution>
            <ol>
              <li><p>Apply Part 1 of <xref ref="thm_limit_algebra">Theorem</xref>.</p></li>

              <li><p>Apply <xref ref="thm_limit_allbut1">Theorem</xref>; <m>g(x) = \frac xx</m> is the same as <m>g(x) = 1</m> everywhere except at <m>x=0</m>. Thus <m>\ds\lim_{x\to0} g(x) = \lim_{x\to 0} 1 = 1.</m></p></li>

              <li><p>The function <m>f(x)</m> is always 0, so <m>g\big(f(x)\big)</m> is never defined as <m>g(x)</m> is not defined at <m>x=0</m>. Therefore the limit does not exist.</p></li>

              <li><p>The Composition Rule requires that <m>\ds\lim_{x\to0} g(x)</m> be equal to <m>g(0)</m>. They are not equal, so the conditions of the Composition Rule are not satisfied, and hence the rule is not violated.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
